WEBVTT
Kind: captions

00:00:00.120 --> 00:00:03.680 position:63% line:0%
There are 11 data types that&nbsp;
RotuerOS variables can have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:03.680 --> 00:00:06.600 position:63% line:0%
let’s have a closer look&nbsp;
to understand them better.

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:13.080 position:63% line:0%
First up we got a variable with no defined value,&nbsp;
which is the first data type – nil. There isn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:17.920 position:63% line:0%
much to see, but I have prepared a little&nbsp;
script snippet that establishes the variable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:24.000 position:63% line:0%
prints it using the ‘put’ command and the&nbsp;
output is an empty line. But then it also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.120 position:63% line:0%
prints the output of a command called ‘typeof’&nbsp;
– this command returns the data type of any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:33.040 position:63% line:0%
variable, and in this case, it is ‘nothing’.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:39.360 position:63% line:0%
Moving on, we got num which is our 64-bit&nbsp;
integer. When we run a similar little script,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:43.920 position:63% line:0%
you can see that the output of the&nbsp;
‘typeof’ command is simply ‘num’. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:49.480 position:63% line:0%
is the only number data type we have, so&nbsp;
when doing math operations like division,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:54.280 position:63% line:0%
we have to keep in mind that there is no&nbsp;
floating data point. If a mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.280 --> 00:01:00.080 position:63% line:0%
operation results in something with a&nbsp;
decimal point, it will simply get rounded.&nbsp;

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:05.480 position:63% line:0%
Normally people don’t want to do advanced math&nbsp;
operations on their routers, so this shouldn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:11.440 position:63% line:0%
be much of a setback. But if you need to do a&nbsp;
precise math operation, you can easily work around&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:17.800 position:63% line:0%
the limitation. For example, if you want to divide&nbsp;
a number with the precision of one decimal place,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:23.600 position:63% line:0%
you could multiply the dividend by 10 and&nbsp;
remember that the rightmost digit is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:30.080 position:63% line:0%
first decimal place. There is also the modulo&nbsp;
operator, which you could use to generate a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:37.160 position:63% line:0%
readable output with multiple decimal places.
A fun fact about the num data type is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:41.280 position:63% line:0%
you could also use bytes in&nbsp;
hexadecimal format as input.

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:47.520 position:63% line:0%
Then we got bool. Not much to it, it just stores&nbsp;
a single bit of information that resembles true&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.480 position:63% line:0%
or false, and hence there are only two&nbsp;
outputs that this variable could have.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:57.640 position:63% line:0%
Strings will take up more memory, but&nbsp;
they can store any text that you need.

00:01:57.640 --> 00:02:04.000 position:63% line:0%
Since this is scripting for routers the next four&nbsp;
data types are for storing networking information.&nbsp;

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:12.080 position:63% line:0%
IP type can efficiently store IPv4 addresses.
IP-prefix is slightly larger and is intended to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:19.280 position:63% line:0%
store the subnet information, but really it&nbsp;
stores the same data as IP plus the subnet.&nbsp;

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:24.960 position:63% line:0%
In the same manner, we have the IP6 type.
And of course, an IP6-prefix&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:30.120 position:63% line:0%
to store the subnet information.
And then we have a special RouterOS variable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:36.000 position:63% line:0%
called ID. It always starts with a star,&nbsp;
but it is just a hexadecimal number.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.640 position:63% line:0%
These are generally used as immutable&nbsp;
references to configurable items. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:48.440 position:63% line:0%
an interface could be referenced using its list&nbsp;
number and name, but both of those could change&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:53.600 position:63% line:0%
breaking your script. So the ID is a&nbsp;
much better way to reference things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:59.200 position:63% line:0%
but they are usually not displayed anywhere. If&nbsp;
you would like to find out the ID you will need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.200 --> 00:03:05.200 position:63% line:0%
to use the ‘get’ command. The information&nbsp;
that is returned will contain the ID.

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:11.160 position:63% line:0%
Now, it is also possible to store time as a&nbsp;
variable. So if I record midnight as a variable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:17.160 position:63% line:0%
it works just fine, but there is a quirk. If&nbsp;
you work with this data type and at any point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:22.640 position:63% line:0%
the value reaches 24 hours,&nbsp;
it will no longer return 24,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:30.240 position:63% line:0%
instead it will turn into 1d00. This is because&nbsp;
the data type stores date and time together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:34.760 position:63% line:0%
but as long as the date part is all&nbsp;
zeroes, they don’t get displayed.&nbsp;

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:39.120 position:63% line:0%
If you want to use this data type to keep&nbsp;
track of things over time, you will have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:46.360 position:63% line:0%
to parse for the full format that starts with&nbsp;
weeks, followed by days, and ends with time.&nbsp;

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:52.120 position:63% line:0%
The 'weeks' number will get pretty large, but ten&nbsp;
thousand is just an example, and it would actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.120 --> 00:04:00.080 position:63% line:0%
be referencing a far future. RouterOS uses the&nbsp;
Unix time which starts on January 1st, 1970.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:08.240 position:63% line:0%
Today's date converted to time data type&nbsp;
would result in something like week 2800.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:13.880 position:63% line:0%
Finally, the last data type is 'array'.&nbsp;
Working with arrays deserves a separate video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:18.680 position:63% line:0%
but here is how you can create them.
To define one, you need to place your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:23.240 position:63% line:0%
values inside curly brackets and&nbsp;
of course, you have to separate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:29.760 position:63% line:0%
them. You can use commas in the input if you&nbsp;
like, but the output will return semicolons.&nbsp;

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:34.080 position:63% line:0%
What is interesting about this data type&nbsp;
is that it can also work similarly to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:39.760 position:63% line:0%
dictionaries in Python, so you could&nbsp;
also define one using key-value pairs.

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:43.040 position:63% line:0%
The funny thing is that you&nbsp;
could even mix them, but more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:51.640 position:63% line:0%
on that in the video on working with arrays.
Thank you for watching and have fun scripting.

